 account for the trait-like, time-invariant stability of the constructs. Traits were more stable than values. The bidirectional effects tended to be significant, but could be distinguished by their relative size. Traits predicted values more strongly than they were predicted by values, and generally predicted well-being and self-esteem more strongly than values did. Traits predicted broad well-being (especially its affective aspects) more strongly than they were predicted by it; values, by contrast, were predicted by well-being (especially its cognitive aspects and self-esteem) more strongly than they predicted it. The findings highlight the central role of traits for personality functioning, while also supporting the mutual constitution of traits and other personality concepts. The results are discussed in the framework of different theoretical approaches to the composition of the broader personality system. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)","2019-08","2024-03-22 04:42:48","2024-03-22 04:42:48","2024-03-22 04:42:47","337",NA,2,117,NA,"","“The longitudinal links of personality traits, values, and well-being and self-esteem",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"English","© 2019, American Psychological Association",NA,NA,NA,"ProQuest",NA,"Num Pages: 337 Place: Washington, US Publisher: American Psychological Association (US)",NA,"/Users/SchoolAccount/Zotero/storage/ADVSN9UC/indicated - 2019 - “The longitudinal links of personality traits, values, and well-being and self-esteem A five-wave s.pdf",NA,NA,"Prediction; Self-Esteem; Personality Traits (major); Well Being (major); Emotions (major); Values (major); Cognition (major); Personality Processes",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA
