tural variability and consistency of sex-differentiated status criteria. The current article investigates status criteria across 14 countries ( N = 2,751). Results provide the first systematic documentation of potentially universal and sex-differentiated status criteria. Discussion outlines important next steps in understanding the psychology of status. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2020 APA, all rights reserved)","2020-11","2024-06-03 18:02:00","2024-06-03 18:02:00","2024-06-03 18:02:00","998",NA,5,119,NA,"","""Human status criteria",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"English","© 2020, American Psychological Association",NA,NA,NA,"ProQuest",NA,"Num Pages: 998 Place: Washington, US Publisher: American Psychological Association (US)",NA,"/Users/SchoolAccount/Zotero/storage/3Y9J69ZS/Buss et al. - 2020 - Human status criteria Sex differences and simila.pdf",NA,NA,"Human Sex Differences (major); Test Construction; Cross Cultural Differences (major); Evolutionary Psychology; Cross Cultural Psychology; Social Groups; Social Status (major)",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA
